        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Prediction of Disk Surface Brightness:

Although SED models are known to be degenerate, they are the best
means to estimate the possible disk extent when proper grain
properties are incorporated. Different sizes of dust particles are
expected to locate at various radii once they are released from their
parent bodies due to stellar radiation pressure. The presence of the
disk halo around HD 95086 illustrates this effect. However, this
grain-size segregation in debris disks is closely tied to the complex
coupling between dynamical and collisional effects (e.g., Thebault et
al. 2013) that despairingly need constraints from observations as we
propose here. Therefore, we adopt the simplest assumptions: a uniform
grain size distribution with a power index of 3.5 at all radii, and
grain properties of icy silicates (30\% of ice by volume on the
surface of compact silicates) that best match the weak ice feature we
detected at 69 um (Fig. 1c, Su et al. in prep.). With the constraints
from the Herschel images and our dynamical stability analysis, we use
our SED models that best match the detailed shape of the disk SED to
estimate the expected disk surface brightness at several ALMA
bands. Disk surface brightness is computed assuming a face-on,
axis-symmetric geometry (no density enhancement/clump), then inclined
to 25 degree from face-on for proper viewing angel. Therefore, our
approach represents a pessimistic view of the system to ensure a
strong detection in reality.

Here we summarize the basic findings in our SED models: (1) the whole
disk SED can be well fitted with one single, very broad Gaussian disk
with the peak radius of 136 AU and a FWHM width of 110 AU, although
its resultant 70 um image contradicts the Herschel observation (termed
extreme case for its lowest surface brightness), (2) a flat disk with
an inner and outer cutoffs of 63 AU and 190 AU (termed as MOD3 or case
1 in our dynamical simulations), and (3) a Gaussian ring with a peaked
radius of 123 AU and a width of 72 AU (termed as MOD4 or case 4 in our
dynamical simulations). The last two models (MOD3 and MOD4) only fit
the disk SED longward of 35 um, while the shorter wavelength excess is
fixed for an inner belt at 7-10 AU. We also construct a 3-component
model (termed MOD6) to account for the extended disk halo at 70 um,
where a range of parameters result in satisfactory fits. This
illustrates the need for the proposed ALMA observation to eliminate
free parameters for the planetesimal belt. MOD6 predicts a similar
disk brightness distribution as MOD3, but in a fainter level similar
to MOD5 (the extreme case).  Our best estimated peak radius of the
planetesimal disk ranges from 0.9'' to 1.5'', and the outer radii are
from 2'' to 3''. Therefore, a single pointing with C34-2 configuration
at Band 6 is chosen.


Sensitivity:

The peak flux at 0.89'' resolution ranges from 0.5 to 0.3 mJy/beam at
Band 6. With a rms noise of 10.4 uJy/beam in a total of 3 hour
on-source integration time, the inner edge of the planetesimal disk
will be detected at S/N of &gt;20, sufficiently enough to determine the
sharpness of the inner boundary of the disk. The expected S/N on the
outer boundary of the disk depends on its exact extent. The request
rms is capable reaching S/N~5 for the extreme case (MOD5). Including
the overheads, a total of 5.6 hours is requested.

 
Correlator:

This project is driven by continuum sensitivity, therefore, we set the
correlator for the maximum bandwidth (7.5 GHz). We also include a
low-resolution line observation configuration to serendipitously
search for CO at 3 km/s resolution (the expected line width is ~twice
of the Keplerian velocity, i.e., 6-7 km/s). Given its young age and
massive nature of the planetesimal belt, it is likely that HD 95086
has some amount of gas in the system (either primordial or
second-generation).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
